ObservedData.Attribute: In 2 adult sisters, born of unrelated Iranian parents (family M135), with neurodevelopmental disorder with dysmorphic facies, impaired speech, and hypotonia (NEDDISH; 619005), Hu et al. (2019) identified compound heterozygous mutations in the MADD gene: a 1-bp deletion (c.3559del, NM_003682), resulting in a frameshift and premature termination (Met1187Ter) and a c.1061C-T transition, resulting in a pro354-to-leu (P354L; 603584.0004) substitution. The mutations were found by exome sequencing and confirmed by Sanger sequencing. The family was part of a large cohort of 404 consanguineous families, mostly Iranian, in which 2 or more offspring had impaired intellectual development. Functional studies of the variants and studies of patient cells were not performed.
